<subSubSection id="C33546A7EF7AA23B8BD5FDE0FB65FCA1" pageId="13" pageNumber="314" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8B90152CEF7AA23B8BD5FDE0FB65FCA1" blockId="13.[151,1437,151,1184]" pageId="13" pageNumber="314">
<emphasis id="B95BC93EEF7AA23B8BD5FDE0FEC9FD88" bold="true" box="[199,321,548,573]" pageId="13" pageNumber="314">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C2F6EAFEF7AA23B8A5BFDE1FDDCFD89" authorityName="Traver ." authorityYear="1947" box="[329,596,549,572]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="314" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cuyuniensis">
<emphasis id="B95BC93EEF7AA23B8A5BFDE1FDDCFD89" box="[329,596,549,572]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="314">Campsurus cuyuniensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from other species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F6EAFEF7AA23B8F56FDE1FB4CFD89" authorityName="Eaton" authorityYear="1868" box="[1092,1220,549,572]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="314" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B95BC93EEF7AA23B8F56FDE1FB4CFD89" box="[1092,1220,549,572]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="314">Campsurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, in the adult stage, by: 1) posterior margin of male abdominal sternum IX convex but medially concave (
<figureCitation id="131409A9EF7AA23B8F7CFD83FB4CFDD5" box="[1134,1220,583,608]" captionStart="FIGURES 51 – 59" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1910,1933]" captionTargetBox="[172,1421,199,1890]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[172,1421,193,1890]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 51 – 59. male imagos. Campsurus cuyuniensis: 51, paratype forceps (CUIC 2434); 52, same but from another paratype; 53, male genitalia from French Guiana specimen (FAMU), v. v. Campsurus nessimiani sp. nov.: 54, genitalia, v. v.; 55, same, l. v. Campsurus dasilvai sp. nov.: 56, genitalia, v. v.; 57, same, l. v.; 58, genitalia, v. v. (SEM), with detail of microlepides on sternum IX; 59, details of penes, v. v. (SEM)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/838448/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="314">Fig. 53</figureCitation>
); 2) pedestals long and slender, well-developed, outer-posterior margin strongly projected forming a long parastylus (apically pointed and curved in lateral view), inner margin also projected but shorter (
<figureCitation id="131409A9EF7AA23B88C3FD4BFBE8FD1D" box="[977,1120,655,680]" captionStart="FIGURES 51 – 59" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1910,1933]" captionTargetBox="[172,1421,199,1890]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[172,1421,193,1890]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 51 – 59. male imagos. Campsurus cuyuniensis: 51, paratype forceps (CUIC 2434); 52, same but from another paratype; 53, male genitalia from French Guiana specimen (FAMU), v. v. Campsurus nessimiani sp. nov.: 54, genitalia, v. v.; 55, same, l. v. Campsurus dasilvai sp. nov.: 56, genitalia, v. v.; 57, same, l. v.; 58, genitalia, v. v. (SEM), with detail of microlepides on sternum IX; 59, details of penes, v. v. (SEM)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/838448/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="314">Figs. 51–53</figureCitation>
); 3) forceps are extremely shortened, thus total length of pedestal (from base to apex of parastylus) is subequal to total forceps length; 4) penes separated and subparallel, formed by a large dorsal sclerotized lobe with acute curved apex, and a relatively large ventral membranous lobe (
<figureCitation id="131409A9EF7AA23B8913FD38FDDDFCA0" box="[513,597,764,789]" captionStart="FIGURES 51 – 59" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1910,1933]" captionTargetBox="[172,1421,199,1890]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[172,1421,193,1890]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 51 – 59. male imagos. Campsurus cuyuniensis: 51, paratype forceps (CUIC 2434); 52, same but from another paratype; 53, male genitalia from French Guiana specimen (FAMU), v. v. Campsurus nessimiani sp. nov.: 54, genitalia, v. v.; 55, same, l. v. Campsurus dasilvai sp. nov.: 56, genitalia, v. v.; 57, same, l. v.; 58, genitalia, v. v. (SEM), with detail of microlepides on sternum IX; 59, details of penes, v. v. (SEM)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/838448/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="314">Fig. 53</figureCitation>
); 5) small size (length of male fore wings ca. 5.4–6.0 mm).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33546A7EF7AA23B8BD5FCDBFC95FB15" pageId="13" pageNumber="314" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B90152CEF7AA23B8BD5FCDBFC95FB15" blockId="13.[151,1437,151,1184]" pageId="13" pageNumber="314">
<emphasis id="B95BC93EEF7AA23B8BD5FCDBFEC4FC8D" bold="true" box="[199,332,799,824]" pageId="13" pageNumber="314">Discussion.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C2F6EAFEF7AA23B8A44FCE4FDECFC8D" authorityName="Traver ." authorityYear="1947" box="[342,612,800,824]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="314" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cuyuniensis">
<emphasis id="B95BC93EEF7AA23B8A44FCE4FDECFC8D" box="[342,612,800,824]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="314">Campsurus cuyuniensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<typeStatus id="5494AB8EEF7AA23B897CFCE4FD16FC8D" box="[622,670,800,824]" pageId="13" pageNumber="314">type</typeStatus>
slides include well-preserved male wings and damaged genitalia. Reliable characters to distinguish the species are found in the male genitalia, but in this case the penes are shrunken, hardly visible and had been separated from the pedestals during slide preparation. Features are visible on these pedestals, however, that positively allow new individuals (those from 
<collectingCountry id="F33855BCEF7AA23B8F1CFC48FB30FC10" box="[1038,1208,908,933]" name="French Guiana" pageId="13" pageNumber="314">French Guiana</collectingCountry>
listed above) to be assigned to 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F6EAFEF7AA23B8A32FC74FE4FFC7D" authorityName="Traver ." authorityYear="1947" box="[288,455,944,968]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="314" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cuyuniensis">
<emphasis id="B95BC93EEF7AA23B8A32FC74FE4FFC7D" box="[288,455,944,968]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="314">C. cuyuniensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: they are large, with parastylus well developed, but forceps are extremely shortened, thus total length of pedestal (from base to apex of parastylus) is subequal to total forceps length (in the 
<typeStatus id="5494AB8EEF7AA23B8E7EFC11FA14FC58" box="[1388,1436,981,1005]" pageId="13" pageNumber="314">type</typeStatus>
material the forceps are slightly shorter,but in the new material are slightly longer). Another unique characteristic of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F6EAFEF7AA23B8BA4FBD9FED4FB81" authorityName="Traver ." authorityYear="1947" box="[182,348,1053,1076]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="314" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cuyuniensis">
<emphasis id="B95BC93EEF7AA23B8BA4FBD9FED4FB81" box="[182,348,1053,1076]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="314">C. cuyuniensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the apical curvature of parastylus in ventral view (
<figureCitation id="131409A9EF7AA23B88A9FBD8FB98FB80" box="[955,1040,1052,1077]" captionStart="FIGURES 51 – 59" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1910,1933]" captionTargetBox="[172,1421,199,1890]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[172,1421,193,1890]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 51 – 59. male imagos. Campsurus cuyuniensis: 51, paratype forceps (CUIC 2434); 52, same but from another paratype; 53, male genitalia from French Guiana specimen (FAMU), v. v. Campsurus nessimiani sp. nov.: 54, genitalia, v. v.; 55, same, l. v. Campsurus dasilvai sp. nov.: 56, genitalia, v. v.; 57, same, l. v.; 58, genitalia, v. v. (SEM), with detail of microlepides on sternum IX; 59, details of penes, v. v. (SEM)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/838448/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="314">Fig. 53</figureCitation>
), but this actually is the result of a dorsal curvature (better seen in lateral view). The penes of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F6EAFEF7AA23B883BFB84FC44FBED" authorityName="Traver ." authorityYear="1947" box="[809,972,1088,1112]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="314" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cuyuniensis">
<emphasis id="B95BC93EEF7AA23B883BFB84FC44FBED" box="[809,972,1088,1112]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="314">C. cuyuniensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
present long and slender lobes (main and secondary), similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F6EAFEF7AA23B8A8AFBA1FDBBFBC9" authority="Molineri &amp; Salles, 2017" authorityName="Molineri &amp; Salles" authorityYear="2017" box="[408,563,1125,1148]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="314" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nessimiani" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B95BC93EEF7AA23B8A8AFBA1FDBBFBC9" box="[408,563,1125,1148]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="314">C. nessimiani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A2687445EF7AA23B892EFBA0FD10FBC8" box="[572,664,1124,1149]" pageId="13" pageNumber="314" rank="species">
<emphasis id="B95BC93EEF7AA23B892EFBA0FD10FBC8" bold="true" box="[572,664,1124,1149]" pageId="13" pageNumber="314">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
, but in the latter species, the apex of the main lobe is spatulate (in lateral view), while in 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F6EAFEF7AA23B8A86FB4CFDBFFB15" authorityName="Traver ." authorityYear="1947" box="[404,567,1160,1184]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="314" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cuyuniensis">
<emphasis id="B95BC93EEF7AA23B8A86FB4CFDBFFB15" box="[404,567,1160,1184]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="314">C. cuyuniensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is acute and curved.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
